## Nested if
We can nest if statements
```python
if x > y:   # first condition is true 
    print("Great, it is over 20 C")  
  else:   # if it is false then this block will be executed  
    if x >5:   # first inner if is true  
        print("It is not very hot or bad")  
    else:   # if x>0 then these code execute  
        print("At least it is above 0 C")  
```

	To help you remember what hour you are in, the number 00 means midnight (after 12), 01 means 1 am, and 13 means midday. 
	So midnight is when the hour hand is pointing at the number 0, 1 am when the hour hand is at number 1, and midday when the hour hand is between
	1 and 12, pointing anywhere between that range.
	A similar convention exists for minutes: 
	the 12th minute is 00, the 13th minute is 01, etc.
	So when the hour hand is in the 1st hour segment  and pointing to the number 1, on a 24 hour clock, the minute hand is pointing at the 01 minute (01 is the 13th
	minute).
	
		In 24 hour time notation, if you see 01-14, a good guess is that the number 14 refers to midday (12pm to 1pm).
		The only exception is if the number 14 is followed by the letter 't', which means time of day (or "to the", as in 14:00t). 
		At any other time, "14" alone will be a 24 hour time without a "t".

## Solution Strategy

### The most frequent number sequence: The input represents the position of each number from 1 to 989 in the sequence.

For each number n, determine the distance between n and the numbers above it. For example, the distance from 757 to 1 is 751, the distance from 1 to 757 (the number above) is 756, the distance from 469 to 757 is 288 and the distance from 11 (the number below) is 777. Note that the distance from any number to any number that is 100 greater, 990 to 757, is 203. There are 49 such pairs. The most frequent such pair occurs when the distance is 203, and there are 17 total such pairs.

Now the final step is to figure out how many pairs are there in all. You can't just count the number of 4 elements, because each pair corresponds to two of them, so you need to subtract all the distance between a group of 4 from all the numbers below a group of 5, and so on, to count the total number of groups.

### If a number sequence repeats itself, the sequence is the most frequent

Input a number, try every single number from 1 to the square of that number.

I made three different lists with values.

List2: Contains numbers from the square-root of n to n.
List3: Contains numbers from n to the square of n.

        j= 190
    else:
        i+=1
        j+=190



print (i)
